{
  "title": "Selecting and Filtering",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b4db22f928d68126",
      "text": "It is obvious that [[Teaching]] always means \"selecting\" and \"filtering\": Even individual world phenomena can never be integrated in their entire complexity into the resonance space of teaching (not to mention the tight time rhythm of a common school day). Some of these reductions therefore remain unavoidable. This process has rightly – and at the same time often problematically – been called \"didactic reduction\" or \"pedagogical care.\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4794f7f917a6c258",
      "text": "*Three* passages are of particular explosiveness:\n\n- One place is the regulations, objectives, media, and materials inserted between world phenomena and instruction, as well as the testing formats – mostly \"standardized\" in such a way that learners' individual needs, interests, and approaches have no place.\n\n- The second point is the scope of action and the self-image of teachers. On the one hand, teachers are left completely alone in the selection of appropriate and meaningful world phenomena by the almost content-free, competence-oriented curriculum. Many teachers feel overwhelmed with this task and use more or less unreflective teaching aids and copy templates, which are then used directly and unchanged in the classroom. Or they fall back on traditional content that has already proven itself in years of teaching practice. On the other hand, teachers are paradoxically completely dependent on the expected development of competencies and the associated standardized tests, since poor test results are immediately seen as the result of poor teaching.\n\n- A third point is the forms of development and mediation of world phenomena: The orientation towards the so-called \"outcome\" neglects the process of appropriation and examination of different contents. The empty space thus created is replaced by sedimented action knowledge from earlier traditions, by which all future teachers were somehow already shaped as pupils.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8c182b4321f1ab8e",
      "text": "Next: German lessons as a dynamic process of [[Perceiving]] – [[Shaping]] – [[Sharing]].\n"
    }
